<gtr:projectOverview xmlns:gtr="http://gtr.ukri.org/api"><gtr:projectComposition><gtr:collaborations/><gtr:leadResearchOrganisation url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/3E18DACB-05AA-4C71-88FB-C909A8311BB5"><gtr:id>3E18DACB-05AA-4C71-88FB-C909A8311BB5</gtr:id><gtr:name>Birkbeck College</gtr:name><gtr:department>Biological Sciences</gtr:department><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Malet Street</gtr:line1><gtr:line4>London</gtr:line4><gtr:postCode>WC1E 7HX</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>London</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:typeInd>RO</gtr:typeInd></gtr:leadResearchOrganisation><gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:organisationRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/3E18DACB-05AA-4C71-88FB-C909A8311BB5"><gtr:id>3E18DACB-05AA-4C71-88FB-C909A8311BB5</gtr:id><gtr:name>Birkbeck College</gtr:name><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Malet Street</gtr:line1><gtr:line4>London</gtr:line4><gtr:postCode>WC1E 7HX</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>London</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>LEAD_RO</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:organisationRole></gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:personRoles><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/BAAC5469-BB9D-4CBF-97FE-164AAC2DA0E2"><gtr:id>BAAC5469-BB9D-4CBF-97FE-164AAC2DA0E2</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Gabriel</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Waksman</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=G0100442"><gtr:id>ECAB03F8-6E96-4563-B0DA-266E3CB7F9D5</gtr:id><gtr:title>Structural Studies of Pilus Biogenesis and Bacterial Adhesion</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Research Grant</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>G0100442</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>We propose here to study the structures of proteins 
involved in the pathogenesis caused by uropathogenic 
Escherichia coli. Urinary tract infections are the 
second most common infections after infections of the 
respiratory tract. The infectious process requires 
adhesive hair-like fibres termed pili . Pili serve 
as attachment devices which allow targeting of the 
bacteria to specific host tissues. A pilus is made of 
a large number of protein subunits which polymerise 
together to form a fibre. At the tip of the pilus, 
there is a sugar-binding protein (or adhesin ) which 
specifically recognises receptors displayed at the 
surface of the host tissue. In this proposal, we plan 
to obtain snapshots of the molecular interactions 
required to assemble pili, and those required by the 
adhesin to recognise its cognate receptor. The planned
 research program outlined here will not only 
contribute to our understanding of pathogenicity 
leading to urinary tract infections but will also 
contribute to our understanding of diseases caused 
by other bacteria that utilize very similar mechanism 
to assemble pili and to recognise their receptor. 
Such bacteria include Haemophilus influenzae 
(causing ottitis media, or meningitis) or Salmonella 
typhimurium (causing gastroenteritis): any insight 
acquired on the uropathogenic E. coli system will 
benefit investigations of a wide range of pathogens. 
Structural studies will also help design new 
antibiotic drugs which will target either pilus 
assembly or bacterial adhesion.</gtr:abstractText><gtr:technicalSummary>The aim of this proposal is to study the structures of 
proteins involved in the pathogenesis caused by 
uropathogenic Escherichia coli, namely pyelonephritis 
(infection of the kidney) and cystitis (infection of 
the bladder). The infectious process requires adhesive 
hair-like fibres termed pili. Pili serve as 
attachment devices which allow targeting of the 
bacteria to a specific host tissue. A pilus is made of 
a large number of protein subunits which polymerise 
together to form a fibre. At the tip of the pilus, 
there is a sugar-binding protein (or adhesin) which 
specifically recognises polysaccharides displayed at 
the surface of the host tissue: this interaction 
determines the selectivity of the bacteria for its
host. Each subunit is 
assembled into a pilus through the conserved 
 chaperone-usher pathway . In this pathway, each 
subunit exists within the periplasm as a stable 
binary complex with a chaperone. Each of these binary 
complexes is targeted to an outer-membrane protein 
usher which serves as site of assembly and where each
subunit polymerises with the subunit assembled 
previously. In recent years, we have discovered that 
each pilus subunit consists of an atypical Ig-like fold 
where the seventh strand is missing. The chaperone, in a 
mechanism that we termed donor-strand 
complementation , complements the fold of the subunit 
by donating the missing strand. During assembly, 
the subunit-chaperone complex targeted to the usher 
dissociates and the missing secondary structure in
the free subunit is donated by the subunit that comes
next. This mechanism 
for pilus subunit polymerisation was termed 
 donor-strand exchange . The present proposal aims at 
contributing further to our understanding of pilus 
assembly and structure. It also aims at deciphering the molecular 
mechanism of receptor-recognition by pilus adhesins.</gtr:technicalSummary><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2008-06-30</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C"><gtr:id>C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C</gtr:id><gtr:name>MRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2003-01-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>1144019</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>F1BCA322-788E-45FF-AF42-6AEA1785B807</gtr:id><gtr:title>Molecular mechanism of P pilus termination in uropathogenic Escherichia coli.</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>EMBO reports</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/fa9d62041c818a3977ca2c113cc5968d"><gtr:id>fa9d62041c818a3977ca2c113cc5968d</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Verger D</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2006-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:issn>1469-221X</gtr:issn><gtr:outcomeId>EE0BF13DCF7</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>37B963AA-2B1D-4126-BA44-B710AABE41A7</gtr:id><gtr:title>Crystal structure of the FimD usher bound to its cognate FimC-FimH substrate.</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Nature</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/314e6eccaf95271c0be31c9305ac64ce"><gtr:id>314e6eccaf95271c0be31c9305ac64ce</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Phan G</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2011-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:issn>0028-0836</gtr:issn><gtr:outcomeId>pJeykWAM14F</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publ